The difference between $@ and $*: Unquoted, the results are unspecified. In Bash, both expand to separate arguments and then are both wordsplit and globbed. Quoted, "$@" expands each element as a separate argument: "$1" "$2" ..., while "$*" expands to all elements merged into one argument: "$1c$2c..." (where c is the first character of IFS). You almost always want "$@". The same goes for arrays:
